## Plan Summary

**Only one file needs to change: `src/routes.ts`.**

Here's what the exploration found and what the plan covers:

### What exists today
- `src/data.ts` — 15 hardcoded `User` objects in memory
- `src/routes.ts` — `GET /users` simply does `res.json(users)` (flat array, no pagination)
- `tests/routes.test.ts` — 6 tests already written (4 for pagination, 2 for `GET /users/:id`), all currently failing for the pagination cases

### The change (single handler rewrite)

```typescript
router.get("/users", (req, res) => {
  const page  = parseInt((req.query.page  as string) ?? "1",  10) || 1;
  const limit = parseInt((req.query.limit as string) ?? "10", 10) || 10;

  const total      = users.length;
  const totalPages = Math.ceil(total / limit);
  const start      = (page - 1) * limit;
  const data       = users.slice(start, start + limit);

  res.json({ data, pagination: { page, limit, total, totalPages } });
});
```

### Why this satisfies all requirements
| Requirement | How |
|---|---|
| Default `page=1`, `limit=10` | `?? "1"` / `?? "10"` + `\|\| 1` / `\|\| 10` fallbacks |
| Correct response shape | Returns `{ data, pagination: { page, limit, total, totalPages } }` |
| Out-of-range → empty array | `Array.slice` beyond bounds returns `[]` naturally |
| Existing tests still pass | `GET /users/:id` is untouched; data layer is untouched |
